com.exceeddata.sdk.vdata.data

Class VDataFrame

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.exceeddata.sdk.vdata.data.VDataFrame
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable

    public class VDataFrame
extends Object
implements Serializable
    A class for two-dimensional tabular data frame that holds signal time-values. Column names can be accessed via method cols(), and signal time-values can be accessed through methods iterator(), objects(), sampling(), object1s depending on the usage scenario.
    See Also:

      • cols

        public List<String> cols()
        Get a list of column names. The order of the column names is same as order of signal values in each row. Time column (at first index) is not included.
        Returns:
        list of column names

      • cols

        public List<String> cols(boolean includeTime)
        Get a list of column names. The order of the column names is same as order of signal values in each row. To include the time column at first index set the includeTime parameter to true.
        Parameters:
        includeTime - whether the list of names includes the time column (at first index)
        Returns:
        list of column names

      • objects

        public Object[][] objects()
                   throws IOException
        Get a sorted 2-d array (row-columns) of of time and all data objects. The values are read all into memory and avoid sorting. It is CPU-efficient but consumes more memory. Therefore, this method is suitable for reading data files smaller than 10MB. The first item of each row is time, followed by values.
        Returns:
        objects
        Throws:
        IOException - if occurs

      • objects

        public Object[][] objects(int densifyRowsAhead)
                   throws IOException
        Return a densified and sorted 2-d array (row-columns) of all data objects. The values are read all into memory and avoid sorting. It is CPU-efficient but consumes more memory. Therefore, this method is suitable for reading data files smaller than 10MB. The first item of each row is time, followed by values.
        Parameters:
        densifyRowsAhead - the number of rows to check to fill initial empty rows. If this value is 0, then no rows are densified.
        Returns:
        densified objects
        Throws:
        IOException - if occurs

      • objects

        public Object[][] objects(int densifyRowsAhead,
                          int densifyOutputItv)
                   throws IOException
        Return a sorted 2-d array (row-columns) of all data objects. If there are more than one data point at the same time, the data point returned is determined by the signal queue mode. The values are read all into memory and avoid sorting. It is CPU-efficient but consumes more memory. Therefore, this method is suitable for reading data files smaller than 10MB. The first item of each row is time.
        Parameters:
        densifyRowsAhead - the number of rows to check to fill initial empty rows.
        densifyOutputItv - the number of milliseconds (interval) to output (vary frequency of) dense data.
        Returns:
        objects
        Throws:
        IOException - if occurs

      • object1s

        public Object[][] object1s()
                    throws IOException
        Return a sorted 2-d array (row-columns) of all data objects at the sampled 1-Hz interval. Note: when we round to the nearest frequency time, it would be better to pick a value at the time closer to the 1s time even if we bend the rules a little bit outside the start/end time filtering but nearer to the 1s.
        Returns:
        objects
        Throws:
        IOException - if occurs

      • sampling

        public Object[][] sampling(int frequency)
                    throws IOException
        Return a sorted 2-d array (row-columns) of all data objects sampled down to the specified frequency in milliseconds. For example, 1-Hz equals a frequency of 1000 (ms). The first item of each row is time, followed by values..
        Parameters:
        frequency - the sampled frequency with value greater than 1.
        Returns:
        objects
        Throws:
        IOException - if occurs

        public Iterator<VDataRow> iterator(int densifyRowsAhead)

        iterator

      • iterator

        public Iterator<VDataRow> iterator(int densifyRowsAhead,
                                   int densifyOutputItv,
                                   int signalQueueRows)
                            throws IOException
        Return an iterator to data rows. If densifyRowsAhead is positive, then data rows are filled in from the specified look-ahead rows (densified), else they are original data rows. If densifyOutputItv is positive, then dense data rows output at recalculated time (cutoff to exact interval), else they output at original data time. if any given interval is entirely missing in original time, then values will be filled in from last available data row.
        Parameters:
        densifyRowsAhead - the number of rows to check to fill initial empty rows.
        densifyOutputItv - the number of milliseconds (interval) to output (vary frequency of) dense data.
        signalQueueRows - the number of rows to cache in each signal queue.
        Returns:
        iterator
        Throws:
        IOException - if I/O exception occurs

      • bkiterator

        public Iterator<Object[]> bkiterator()
                              throws IOException
        Return an iterator sorted 2-d array (row-columns) of data objects. The data objects are read one bucket by bucket. The first item of each row is time.
        Returns:
        iterator
        Throws:
        IOException - if occurs

      • bkiterator

        public Iterator<Object[]> bkiterator(int densifyRowsAhead,
                                     int densifyOutputItv,
                                     boolean sparseDataContent)
                              throws IOException
        Return an iterator sorted 2-d array (row-columns) of data objects. The data objects are read one bucket by bucket. Note: densify not yet supported but the parameter is left in place. The first item of each row is time.
        Parameters:
        densifyRowsAhead - the number of rows to check to fill initial empty rows.
        densifyOutputItv - the number of milliseconds (interval) to output (vary frequency of) dense data.
        sparseDataContent - whether the data is sparse, false if the data is dense.
        Returns:
        iterator
        Throws:
        IOException - if occurs
